explanation:
For each symbol:

- OS_StatusToInteger
  Reason: The function is called inside OS_StatusToString. To decide whether removing the call (or the snprintf that uses its result) would change program behaviour we must know whether OS_StatusToInteger has observable side-effects (mutating globals, I/O, volatile accesses, etc.) or whether it is pure. If it has side-effects, the call is not dead even if its numeric result is unused elsewhere.

- os_status_string_t (typedef / concrete type)
  Reason: sizeof(*status_string) and the semantics of writing into *status_string depend on the concrete type (array, pointer to buffer length, volatile qualifiers, etc.). If the buffer is e.g. a special shared/volatile object, writes by snprintf are observable and cannot be removed. Also needed to see if the type is zero-sized, flexible, or contains side-effecting members.

- snprintf (or any build-time wrapper/macro used instead)
  Reason: snprintf performs the buffer write; its behaviour (and possible side-effects) determines whether removing the snprintf call would alter program behaviour. In some builds snprintf may be replaced by a test stub or macro with side-effects — you must inspect the actual symbol used.

- declaration/linkage of OS_StatusToString (prototype / static/extern attribute)
  Reason: Linkage and visibility affect whether the function can be called from other translation units or exported (making it observable even if static call-graph shows no callers). If it is externally visible or weak, it may be used by external code, so the function (or parts of it) may not be dead.

- all callers of OS_StatusToString (or confirmation that there are none)
  Reason: Dead-code determination for a function (or code within it) depends on whether the function is ever invoked. If there are no callers and no other references, the whole function may be dead. Conversely, if callers exist, you must inspect their usage to see if the writes/return value are observable.

- all address-taken / function-pointer references to OS_StatusToString (&OS_StatusToString occurrences)
  Reason: The function can be used indirectly through pointers or registered as a callback; address-taken references make the function reachable even if static call-graph shows no direct callers. Such indirect uses can make the code observable and thus not dead.

- unit-test/mock stubs that can replace snprintf or OS_StatusToInteger (e.g. UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr)
  Reason: The provided static call graph suggests the build/test environment may replace or instrument snprintf/OS_StatusToInteger with UT framework stubs. Those stubs can introduce side-effects or change observability. To decide if the snprintf/OS_StatusToInteger calls are removable, the actual implementations (or mocks) used in the target build must be inspected.

Collecting these symbols (types, implementations, callers, and any test/mocking wrappers) provides the information needed to determine whether the calls and buffer writes inside OS_StatusToString are observable — if they are observable then removal would change program behaviour and thus they are not dead code; if they are not observable in any reachable execution, they may be considered dead.
